<!-- FAQ Section -->
<section id="faq-wire-o" class="mb-5 pb-4">
  <h2 class="mb-3">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>
  <div class="accordion" id="faqAccordion">
    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-header" id="faq1">
        <h3 class="h5 mb-0">
          <button
            class="faq-toggle collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-toggle="collapse"
            data-target="#collapse1"
          >
            How many pages can Wire-O binding handle?
            <span class="faq-icon"><i class="bi bi-chevron-down"></i></span>
          </button>
        </h3>
      </div>
      <div id="collapse1" class="collapse" data-parent="#faqAccordion">
        <div class="faq-content">
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>
              Wire-O binding can typically accommodate between 20 and 250 sheets
              (40-500 pages). The exact capacity depends on paper weight and
              wire diameter. For reference:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>20lb bond paper: up to 250 sheets</li>
              <li>28lb premium paper: up to 200 sheets</li>
              <li>70lb text weight: up to 150 sheets</li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              For documents under 20 sheets, the binding may not be secure
              enough—consider saddle-stitch binding instead. For documents over
              250 sheets, you'll need to split into multiple volumes or choose
              perfect binding.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-header" id="faq2">
        <h3 class="h5 mb-0">
          <button
            class="faq-toggle collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-toggle="collapse"
            data-target="#collapse2"
          >
            What's the difference between Wire-O and spiral coil binding?
            <span class="faq-icon"><i class="bi bi-chevron-down"></i></span>
          </button>
        </h3>
      </div>
      <div id="collapse2" class="collapse" data-parent="#faqAccordion">
        <div class="faq-content">
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>
              Both allow pages to lay flat and rotate 360°, but there are key
              differences:
            </p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Wire-O:</strong> Uses twin metal loops that interlock.
                More professional appearance, slightly more durable, but can
                snag on fabric. Better for business documents and presentations.
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Spiral Coil:</strong> Uses a single continuous plastic
                or metal coil. Less likely to snag, can hold slightly more
                pages, costs 10-20% less. Better for documents that will be
                carried frequently.
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              For most small business applications like reports and manuals,
              Wire-O provides the best balance of appearance and functionality.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-header" id="faq3">
        <h3 class="h5 mb-0">
          <button
            class="faq-toggle collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-toggle="collapse"
            data-target="#collapse3"
          >
            Can I add or remove pages from a Wire-O bound book?
            <span class="faq-icon"><i class="bi bi-chevron-down"></i></span>
          </button>
        </h3>
      </div>
      <div id="collapse3" class="collapse" data-parent="#faqAccordion">
        <div class="faq-content">
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>
              Technically yes, but it requires specialized equipment. You would
              need to:
            </p>
            <ol>
              <li>Un-crimp the wire ends (requires a wire closer tool)</li>
              <li>Thread the wire out of all the pages</li>
              <li>Add or remove pages</li>
              <li>Re-thread the wire through all pages</li>
              <li>Cut and crimp the wire ends again</li>
            </ol>
            <p>
              For most users, it's easier to simply reorder the book with
              updated content. However, if you regularly need to update
              materials, consider loose-leaf ring binders which are designed for
              easy page changes.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="card">
      <div class="card-header" id="faq4">
        <h3 class="h5 mb-0">
          <button
            class="faq-toggle collapsed"
            type="button"
            data-toggle="collapse"
            data-target="#collapse4"
          >
            What file format should I submit for printing?
            <span class="faq-icon"><i class="bi bi-chevron-down"></i></span>
          </button>
        </h3>
      </div>
      <div id="collapse4" class="collapse" data-parent="#faqAccordion">
        <div class="faq-content">
          <div class="faq-body">
            <p>We accept several formats, but PDF is strongly preferred:</p>
            <ul>
              <li>
                <strong>Best:</strong> PDF/X-1a or PDF/X-4 with embedded fonts
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Good:</strong> Standard PDF with fonts embedded and
                images at 300 DPI
              </li>
              <li>
                <strong>Acceptable:</strong> Microsoft Word, PowerPoint (but
                we'll convert to PDF and may need to confirm formatting)
              </li>
            </ul>
            <p>
              Make sure to use CMYK color mode (not RGB) and include 0.125"
              bleed on the top, bottom, and outside edges. Keep important
              content at least 0.5" away from the binding edge.
            </p>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>
